Arguably the most prominent thinker in the classical western thought system, Plato wrote the foregoing verdict around 380 B.C. and it still finds enormous relevance in modern societies. Having witnessed the unjust trial and execution of his teacher and mentor, Socrates, Plato saw the evil of democratic system of government and ruling elites lacking the virtue of knowledge to reorganise the state justly. And to undo those evils, he wrote his magnum opus,Â The Republic, as a classic in statecraft where knowledge or ideas complement political power to deliver effective leadership. 